2.1. The structure and the dimensions of the data

Data set includes seven variables: gender, age, attitude, deep, stra, surf and points. There are 166 participants (110 female and 56 male) in the data. Age range was from 21 to 55 years. Over half of the participants were from 20 to 23 years old (N=88).

The outcomes of deep, stra and surf depict deep, surface, and strategic approach of study skills from the measure of Approaches and Study Skills Inventory for Students. Deep-outcome is composed by summing 12 questions, that ask about “seeking meaning”, “relating ideas”, and “use of evidence”, and then divided by the number of the items of the scale (range: 1-5). Surf-outcome is composed by summing 12 questions, that ask about “lack of purpose”, “unrelated memorising”, and “syllabus-boundeness”, and then divided by the number of the items of the scale (range: 1-5). In addition, Stra-outcome includes the mean of 8 items, that measure “organized studying” and “time management”. Lastly, there are Points-outcome that includes the total score from all the questions.

The results show that the model is not statistically significant (F(3, 162) = 2.292, p = 0.08). The estimated effect of deep approach is -0.74 (p = 0.39), while the estimated effect for strategic approach is 0.99 (p = 0.10) and for surface approach -1.63 (0.08).

In the model1 2.3 % of the varince in the points can be predicted by the three outcomes.

Model2:

In the model 2, deep approach outcome is excluded from the model 1, and it is summarized here:

model2 <- lm(points ~ stra + surf, data = learning2014.data)

summary(model2)

## Residuals:

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.822 on 163 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.03634,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.02452 
## F-statistic: 3.074 on 2 and 163 DF,  p-value: 0.04895

The results depict that the model is now statistically significant (F(2, 163) = 3.074, p = 0.049). The estimated effect for strategic approach is 0.96 (p = 0.11) and for surface approach -1.38 (p = 0.11). This means that more strategic approach and less surface approach predicts the higher the points. However, even though the model is statistically significant, the the estimated effect are insignificant for independent variables.*

In the model2, 2.5 % of the variance in the points (adjusted R-squared) can be predicted by the two outcomes.

2.5. The diagnostic plots.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(model2)

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

There is the assumption of homoscedasticity in the model.

In a plot of residual vs fitted values red line represent the mean of the residuals. It supposed to be horizontal and centered around zero. This means there are no outliers or biases in the data that would make a linear regression invalid.In the model2, there are a little bias in small and large values of the points.

In the Normal Q-Qplot in the top right, you can see that the real residuals from model2 form an almost perfectly one-to-one line with the theoretical residuals from a perfect model when theoretical qouantiles are [-1, 1]

Based on these residuals, we can say that our model meets the assumption of homoscedasticity at least to a certain extent.

In the plot residuals vs leverage is shown several influential points that are below Cook’s distance. Leverage refers to the extent to which the coefficients in the regression model would change if a particular observation was removed from the dataset. Based on the results, there might be an option that another regression model would better fit in or the influential observations should be handle in another way.

3.1 The description of the data

This data approach student achievement in secondary education of two Portuguese schools. The data attributes include student grades, demographic, social and school related features (35 variables) and it was collected by using school reports and questionnaires. Two data sets were first provided regarding the performance in two distinct subjects: Mathematics (mat) and Portuguese language (por). In this report I used a joined data set, where I made following adjustment: the grade variables were combined by averaging in math and Portuguese, ‘alc_use’ outcome was an average of workday alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high) and weekend alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high), and ‘hig_use’ outcome provide information if alc use was higher than 2. There were 370 participants in the study, of which 195 were females. Age range was from 15 to 22 years.

3.2 Personal hypothesis about the relationships of outcomes with alcohol consumption

I chose the variables of sex, final grade, number of school absences and current health status, to study their relationships to high/low alcohol consumption. My personal hypothesis were that 1) males have higher alcohol consumption than females, as well as 2) lower final grade, 3) higher number of school absences and 4) lower health status are predicted higher consumption.

Mean of health status was lower in high consumption group. In females, however, there was little difference on means of health between high and low consumption groups (0.02). The health status was lowest in males with high consumption.

3.5 Predictive power of the model

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(boot)
## Warning: package 'boot' was built under R version 4.2.2
library(ggplot2)

# fit the model with outcomes of statistically significant relationships
model1 <- glm(high_use ~ G3 + absences + sex, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(model1, type = "response")

library(dplyr)
# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)


# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   248   11
##    TRUE     83   28
#table for probabilities
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction) %>% prop.table()
##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE
##    FALSE 0.67027027 0.02972973
##    TRUE  0.22432432 0.07567568
#add margins
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction) %>% prop.table() %>% addmargins()
##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE        Sum
##    FALSE 0.67027027 0.02972973 0.70000000
##    TRUE  0.22432432 0.07567568 0.30000000
##    Sum   0.89459459 0.10540541 1.00000000
#plot
library(ggplot2)
g2 <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = probability, y = high_use, col = prediction))
g2 + geom_point()

# define a loss function (average prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2540541

The total proportion of inaccurately classified individual i.e., the training error is 0.25 for the model. Performance of the the model is similar than simple guessing strategy.

4.1 The description of Boston data

The Boston data frame has 506 rows and 14 columns. The columns are following:

crim: per capita crime rate by town. zn: proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft. indus: proportion of non-retail business acres per town. chas: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise). nox: nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million). rm: average number of rooms per dwelling. age: proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940. dis: weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres. rad: index of accessibility to radial highways. tax: full-value property-tax rate per $10,000. ptratio: pupil-teacher ratio by town. black: 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2, where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town. lstat: lower status of the population (percent). medv: median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 3)

#Then predict the classes with the LDA model on the test data. Cross tabulate the results with the crime categories from the test set.


# predict classes with test data
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

# cross tabulate the results
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)

##   low       16      11        2    0
##   med_low    2      16        9    0
##   med_high   0       5       20    1
##   high       0       0        0   20
#find accuracy of model

## [1] 0.7058824

The percentage separation achieved by each linear discriminant function are for LD1: 95 %, LD2: 4 % and for LD3: 1%

Cross tabulations and test for accuracy of the model shows that the model correctly predicted 65 % of the crimes in the data set.

# load the data
data("Boston")

#standardized data set
boston_scaled <- scale(Boston, center = TRUE, scale = TRUE)

# change the object to data frame
boston_scaled <- as.data.frame(boston_scaled)

#distances
dist_eu <- dist(boston_scaled, method = "euclidean")

# look at the summary of the distances
summary(dist_eu)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1343  3.4625  4.8241  4.9111  6.1863 14.3970
# k-means clustering

# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

# k-means clustering
km <- kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 2)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(boston_scaled[1:5], col = km$cluster)

pairs(boston_scaled[6:10], col = km$cluster)

In the investigation of the optimal number of cluster we see that 2 might be the case. However, in the plot of the number of clusters and the total WCSS, the optimal number of clusters is not quite clear as there is not a radical drops of the total WCSS.
